triglyceride synthesis in the liver","Enhanced fatty acid oxidation","Increased phospholipid synthesis"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe primary mechanism by which alcohol induces fatty liver disease is through \u003Cstrong\u003Eincreased triglyceride synthesis in the liver\u003C/strong\u003E. Alcohol metabolism increases the availability of fatty acids and glycerol, which are substrates for triglyceride formation. Additionally, alcohol can impair the secretion of very low density lipoprotein (VLDL), leading to triglyceride accumulation in the liver.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIncreased supply of fatty acids from adipose tissue\u003C/strong\u003E - While alcohol can increase fatty acid mobilisation, the key issue is the liver\u0027s increased synthesis and decreased export of triglycerides\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDecreased synthesis of very low density lipoprotein apolipoprotein\u003C/strong\u003E - This contributes to triglyceride accumulation but is not the primary mechanism\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEnhanced fatty acid oxidation\u003C/strong\u003E - Alcohol decreases fatty acid oxidation\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIncreased phospholipid synthesis\u003C/strong\u003E - This is not a primary factor in alcohol-induced fatty liver disease\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Alcohol consumption can lead to fatty liver disease by increasing triglyceride synthesis in the liver.","Alcohol metabolism increases the availability of fatty acids and glycerol, promoting triglyceride formation.","Decreased very low density lipoprotein (VLDL) secretion contributes to triglyceride accumulation in the liver."],"references":["Gilbert-Barness, E., Barness, L. A., \u0026 Farrell, P. M. (Eds.). (2017). Metabolic diseases: foundations of clinical management, genetics, and pathology. IOS Press","Lanham-New, S. A., Macdonald, I. A., \u0026 Roche, H. M. (Eds.). (2011). Nutrition and metabolism. John Wiley \u0026 Sons","Roche, H. M., Macdonald, I. A., Schols, A. M., \u0026 Lanham-New, S. A. (Eds.). (2024). Nutrition and metabolism. John Wiley \u0026 Sons","Omiecinski CJ, Vanden Heuvel JP, Perdew GH, Peters JM. Xenobiotic metabolism, disposition, and regulation by receptors: from biochemical phenomenon to predictors of major toxicities. Toxicol Sci. 2011 Mar;120 Suppl 1(Suppl 1):S49-75. doi: 10.1093/toxsci/kfq338. Epub 2010 Nov 8. PMID: 21059794; PMCID: PMC3145385","Kumar, V., Abbas, A. K., \u0026 Aster, J. C. (Eds.). (2012). Robbins basic pathology e-book. Elsevier Health Science"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64534"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17983"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64534","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/64534"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-13T16:35:19+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-13T16:35:42+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10697"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"79182"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"d